#Task 5 - R Functions
#1. Write a function that calculates the ratio of the mean and the median of a given vector.

fun1 <- function(vector){ # create fun1
  mean_vector <-mean(vector) #calculate mean of input vector
  median_vector <- median(vector)#calculate median of input vector
  return(mean_vector/median_vector) #return the ratio 
}

#test 
test1 <- c(1,2,3,4,5) #create test data
fun1(test1) #test
## [1] 1
#2. Write a function that ignores the lowest and the highest value from a given vector and calculate the mean.

fun2 <- function(vector){#create fun2 
  
  max <- max(vector)#calculate max number of vector 
  min <- min(vector)#calculate min number of vector 
  delete <- c(max,min)#make max and min into a new vector
  filter_vec <- vector[-delete]#delete the new vector from input vector
  return(mean(filter_vec))#reture the filtered vector 
}

#test 
test2 <- c(1,2,3)#test data
fun2(test2)#test
## [1] 2

  filter(species == 'jedi')  #select data with 'jedi'species

#b. Count the missing values per gene and visualize this result.
NA_count <- data.frame(gene= colnames(microarray_data),count = colSums(is.na(microarray_data)))

#ggplot visualize
ggplot(NA_count, aes(x = gene, y = count)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(x = "gene", y = "Missing Count") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

#c. Find the genes for which there are more than X% (X=10%, 20%, 50%) missing values.

#calculate missing percentage 
NA_count <- NA_count %>%
  mutate(NA_percent = count/553)

#select using dplyr
Over10P <- NA_count %>%
  filter(NA_percent > 0.1) %>%
  select(gene)

Over20P <- NA_count %>%
  filter(NA_percent > 0.2) %>%
  select(gene)

Over50P <- NA_count %>%
  filter(NA_percent > 0.5) %>%
  select(gene)

#d. Replace the missing values by the average expression value for the particular gene. (Note: Imputing data has to be used with caution!)

#write a function to replace all NA with mean in one column
replace_function <- function(column){
  mean_value <- mean(column, na.rm = TRUE)  # Calculate the mean values
  column[is.na(column)] <- mean_value  # Replace NAs with the mean
  return(column)
}

new_microarray_data <-  apply(microarray_data,2,replace_function) #use apply function to run this on all columns

#a. Extract summary statistics (mean, median and maximum) for the following variables from the chromosome data: variations, protein coding genes, and miRNAs. Utilize the tidyverse functions to make this as simply as possible.
library(tidybiology) 
data("chromosome") #load data
summary <- chromosome %>% #obtain mean max median using dplyr 
  summarise(variations_mean = mean(variations),
            variations_median = median(variations),
            variations_max = max(variations),
            protein_codinggenes_mean = mean(protein_codinggenes),
            protein_codinggenes_median = median(protein_codinggenes),
            protein_codinggenes_max = max(protein_codinggenes),
            miRNAs_mean = mean(mi_rna),
            miRNAs_median = median(mi_rna),
            miRNAs_max = max(mi_rna))

print(summary)
